      Artificial intelligence
   =20
 =20

Here is  a surprising statistic:
AI is also expensive, both to develop and to run. Estimates show the costs =
of using large language models to answer a question can be as much as $14 p=
er query, compared with $6 via a human lawyer, according to Lewis Z. Liu, f=
ounder and CEO at Eigen. That=E2=80=99s because of the extensive cloud comp=
uting costs associated with dealing with complex financial documents.
Umm! My understanding is that a fairly junior lawyer=C2=A0at a big law firm=
=C2=A0can bill $1,000 per hour. Six dollars would buy about 22 seconds of h=
er time. You could probably get a lawyer to answer a question like =E2=80=
=9Cis it raining outside your office right now?=E2=80=9D for less than=C2=
=A0you=E2=80=99d pay a large language model=C2=A0(and get a more accurate a=
nswer!), but if your question  is more like =E2=80=9Cif the target of my me=
rger agreement won=E2=80=99t give me all the information I have requested a=
bout bots, what provisions of the merger agreement might allow me to walk a=
way from the deal, and what are my odds of success,=E2=80=9D ChatGPT is def=
initely going to be cheaper. Will it be better? Probably not! But surely no=
 one in the history of the world has ever before said =E2=80=9Cthe nice thi=
ng about lawyers is that they will happily answer questions for $6 a pop.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That statistic is from   a Bloomberg story about how financial firms are us=
ing artificial intelligence tools to do, well, a little of everything:

The AI revolution is unfolding on Wall Street as wider interest grows in th=
e evolving technology and its likely impact on business. At the most enthus=
iastic banks, about 40% of all open job roles are for AI-related hires such=
 as data engineers and quants, as well as ethics and governance roles, acco=
rding to new data from consultancy Evident. =E2=80=A6
The potential prize for businesses is that everyday tasks will be handled m=
ore efficiently and effectively while complex analysis and risk modeling ar=
e made easier and faster. That=E2=80=99s particularly tempting in banking, =
where reams of data underpin increasingly complex investment decisions, des=
pite uncertainties about AI=E2=80=99s eventual capabilities and concerns ab=
out how to regulate it.
The process has already begun, according to lawyers advising lenders on tec=
hnology and regulatory issues. Banks are using AI =E2=80=9Cto come up with =
more tailored hedging solutions through instruments like interest-rate swap=
s and equity derivatives, enabling them to offer better pricing to clients,=
=E2=80=9D said Steven Burrows, a director at Fieldfisher LLP and a former d=
erivatives trader.

No idea what that means but it sounds fun! And:
Wells Fargo is using large language models to help determine what informati=
on clients must report to regulators and how they can improve their busines=
s processes. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt takes away some of the repetitive grunt work=
 and at the same time we are faster on compliance,=E2=80=9D said Chintan Me=
hta, the firm=E2=80=99s chief information officer and head of digital techn=
ology and innovation. The bank has also built a chatbot-based customer assi=
stant using Google Cloud=E2=80=99s conversational AI platform, Dialogflow.
Do you think that Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s customer chatbot pushes customers t=
o  open more accounts to meet its quotas? Do you think that its regulatory-=
reporting chatbot then reports it to regulators? Soon Wells Fargo may be ab=
le to generate and negotiate billion-dollar regulatory settlements without =
any human involvement at all.=C2=A0
The downside =E2=80=94=C2=A0besides paying $14 per question I guess =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is that large language models are known to sometimes be confident =
and wrong:
Bankers have a fiduciary duty not to trade on unreliable information. That=
=E2=80=99s an issue as use of AI expands, according to Anne Beaumont, partn=
er at Friedman Kaplan Seiler Adelman & Robbins LLP in New York. =E2=80=9CHo=
w do you demonstrate to investors and regulators that you=E2=80=99ve done y=
our duty when you=E2=80=99ve used an output without really knowing what the=
 inputs are?=E2=80=9D she said.
And another Bloomberg story, this one  about hedge funds using AI to automa=
te tasks, adds:
The technology isn=E2=80=99t perfect, however. ChatGPT has been known to ma=
ke up facts and spit out different responses to the same prompt, and is onl=
y trained on data up to late 2021. Meanwhile, in an industry where trade se=
crets are anxiously guarded, many are still hesitant about relying on exter=
nal software.=C2=A0
Isn=E2=80=99t this sort of exciting? The widespread use of relatively early=
-stage AI will introduce=C2=A0new ways of making mistakes=C2=A0into finance=
. Right now there are some classic ways of making mistakes in finance, and =
they periodically lead to consequences ranging from funny embarrassment thr=
ough multimillion-dollar trading loss up to systemic financial crises. Many=
 of the most classic mistakes have the broad shape of =E2=80=9Coverly confi=
dent generalizing from limited historical data,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0though some a=
re, like,  hitting the wrong button. But there are only so many ways to go =
wrong, and they are all sort of intuitive.
But now there are new ways! Weird ways! Oh sure an AI can probably make ove=
rly confident generalizations from limited historical data, but perhaps the=
re is room for novelty. Now some banker is going to type into a chat bot =
=E2=80=9Cour client wants to hedge the risk of the Turkish election,=E2=80=
=9D and the chat bot will be like =E2=80=9Cshe should sell some Dogecoin ca=
ll options and use the proceeds to buy a lot of nickel futures,=E2=80=9D an=
d the banker will be like =E2=80=9Cweird okay whatever.=E2=80=9D And that t=
rade will go wrong in surprising ways,=C2=A0=C2=A0the client will sue,=C2=
=A0the client and the banker and the chat bot will all come to court,=C2=A0=
the judge will ask the chat bot =E2=80=9Cwell why would this trade hedge an=
ything,=E2=80=9D and the chat bot will shrug its little imaginary shoulders=
 and be like =E2=80=9Cbro why are you asking me I=E2=80=99m a chat bot.=E2=
=80=9D Or it will say =E2=80=9Cactually the Dogecoin/nickel spread was ex a=
nte=C2=A0an excellent proxy for Turkish political risk because=E2=80=9D and=
 then emit=C2=A0a series of ones and zeros and emojis and high-pitched nois=
es that you and I and the judge can=E2=80=99t understand but that make perf=
ect sense to the chat bot. New ways to be wrong! It will make life more exc=
iting for financial columnists, for a bit, before we are all replaced by th=
e chat bots.
Elsewhere in lawyers and AI and confident wrongness, here is a story about =
