When a company does an initial public offering, it files a registration sta=
tement=C2=A0with the US Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0with a pros=
pectus containing=C2=A0financial statements and a description of its busine=
ss and other relevant details. If you buy stock in the IPO=C2=A0and=C2=A0th=
e stock goes down, and if something in the prospectus is misleading, you ca=
n sue the company, and the underwriters of the IPO, for damages. You would =
sue under section 11 of the Securities Act of 1933, which lets you sue if t=
he registration statement=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccontained an untrue statement of a =
material fact or omitted to state a material fact required to be stated the=
rein or necessary to make the statements therein not misleading.=E2=80=9D I=
n fact, if you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0buy stock directly in the IPO, but b=
uy it in the open market the day or week or month after the IPO, you can al=
so sue under section 11: Your shares are =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=9D to the=
 IPO, and you could have been misled by the company=E2=80=99s bad prospectu=
s into buying the stock.
Now, if you buy stock in a mature public company years after its IPO, and t=
he stock goes down, you can=C2=A0also sue the company. =E2=80=9CEverything =
is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I like to say. The company puts out lots of p=
ublic disclosures, and you can probably point to one of them and say "hey t=
hat was misleading, and when the truth came out my stock went down.=E2=80=
=9D Technically here you would be suing under  section 10 of the Securities=
 Exchange Act of 1934, which makes it illegal for anyone to use =E2=80=9Can=
y manipulative or deceptive device or contrivance=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cin=
 connection with the purchase or sale of any security.=E2=80=9D
In general, if you can, you would rather sue under section 11 of the =E2=80=
=9933 Act than section 10 of the =E2=80=9934 Act. For one thing, it is easi=
er to prove an =E2=80=9Cuntrue statement of material fact=E2=80=9D than a =
=E2=80=9Cmanipulative or deceptive device or contrivance.=E2=80=9D (Lawyers=
 say that section 10 requires =E2=80=9Cscienter=E2=80=9D: Roughly, you need=
 to prove the company=C2=A0was lying, not just mistaken.) For another thing=
, section 11 lets you sue the underwriters =E2=80=94=C2=A0the investment ba=
nks that led the IPO =E2=80=94=C2=A0while section 10 doesn=E2=80=99t, becau=
se there are no underwriters, because there is no offering.
And so stock-drop lawsuits that stem from an IPO are more valuable than sto=
ck-drop lawsuits that don=E2=80=99t: If a company says something wrong in i=
ts IPO prospectus and the stock drops, its shareholders have a good lawsuit=
; if a company says something wrong in its annual report years after its IP=
O and the stock drops, the shareholders have a less good lawsuit. And this =
makes sense: The law is stricter on companies that are=C2=A0going=C2=A0publ=
ic; it tries to make sure that companies introduce themselves to the public=
 honestly and that their underwriters are willing to vouch for them. Once a=
 company has been public for a while, there is a higher bar for complaining=
 that its public filings are a trick.
A few years ago there was a bit of a fad for   direct listings, in which co=
mpanies went public without an IPO. Instead of hiring an underwriter to sel=
l a big block of stock at a fixed price, companies would just open for trad=
ing on the stock exchange one day, and start trading at whatever price the =
market settled on. When this started, it was a way to become a public compa=
ny without selling stock: Existing shareholders (founders, employees, ventu=
re capitalists) were just allowed to sell stock one day, but the company it=
self did not raise money by selling stock. (Since then, the stock exchanges=
 have created rules to allow companies to   raise money using direct listin=
gs.)=C2=A0
One question is: If you buy stock in a direct listing, and the stock drops =
and you have complaints about the company=E2=80=99s disclosure, do you get =
to sue under section 11 (because it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0basically=C2=A0an IPO), =
or do you have to sue under section 10 (because it is=C2=A0not actually=C2=
=A0an IPO)?=C2=A0=C2=A0
Slack Technologies Inc. went public through a direct listing in June 2019. =
It shot up to $38.62 on its first day of trading, and then fell=C2=A0to as =
low as $20.13 by November. (It was acquired by Salesforce Inc. for about $4=
5 in cash and stock in July 2021.) People who bought early and saw the stoc=
k drop naturally sued, complaining that Slack=E2=80=99s disclosures were wr=
ong. I don=E2=80=99t know what disclosures they had complaints about; that =
is rarely the point in these things. Instead, the important question was wh=
ether they get to sue under section 11 or not. An appeals court ruled that =
they did, but Slack appealed to the US Supreme Court, and   today Slack won=
:

The US Supreme Court limited the ability of shareholders to sue over mislea=
ding statements issued by companies when they go public through a direct li=
sting, giving a partial victory to=C2=A0Salesforce Inc.=E2=80=99s Slack uni=
t.
The justices on Thursday unanimously=C2=A0set aside=C2=A0a ruling that had =
let a shareholder suit go forward. Writing for the court, Justice=C2=A0Neil=
 Gorsuch=C2=A0said federal securities law authorizes lawsuits over registra=
tion statements only by people who hold shares issued under those documents=
. ...
The justices were considering a suit by Fiyyaz Pirani, who alleges that Sla=
ck=E2=80=99s 2019 registration statement failed to disclose the extent to w=
hich the company would have to provide credits to customers over service di=
sruptions. Salesforce acquired Slack in 2021.
Salesforce contends Pirani lacks legal standing to sue under the 1933 Secur=
ities Act because he can=E2=80=99t prove he bought registered shares. The S=
upreme Court ruling leaves open the possibility that Pirani can show that a=
t least some of the 250,000 shares he says he bought were registered.=C2=A0

Here is=C2=A0the=C2=A0opinion. The issue here is pretty strange. Basically =
the way it works is that, in an IPO, a company sells stock into the market,=
 and anyone who buys stock that day, or the next day, or the next week, nec=
essarily buys shares that were registered and sold in the IPO. In a typical=
 IPO, the company=C2=A0(and some of its private shareholders: founders, ven=
ture capitalists, etc.) will register with the SEC and sell a big block of =
stock,=C2=A0perhaps 20% of the outstanding shares, and these are the shares=
 that are available for public trading that day and the next day and the ne=
xt week. The=C2=A0rest=C2=A0of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0the 80% still owned=
 by founders, employees, venture or private-equity backers, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0will not be available for trading for a while, mostly because of lock=
up agreements preventing insiders from selling it.
  [1]
=C2=A0Gorsuch:
To prevent the stock price from falling once public trading begins, underwr=
iters may require insiders to consent to a =E2=80=9Clockup agreement=E2=80=
=9D=E2=80=94a commitment to hold their unregistered shares for a period of =
time before selling them on the new public market.
This means that every share that changes hands is =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=
=9D to the IPO: 100% of the publicly traded shares were sold in the IPO, so=
 if you buy stock that week you definitely bought IPO shares issued by the =
company under a registration statement. And the way the law works is that, =
if you buy shares =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=9D to the IPO and the IPO prospe=
ctus, you can sue under section 11 for misstatements in the prospectus.=C2=
=A0
In a direct listing, similarly, some of the bigger shareholders have to reg=
ister their share sales, and so there will be a registration statement and =
prospectus.  Here is Slack=E2=80=99s. But other shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0small employee shareholders, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0can sell their stock im=
mediately without registration, and (as is often true of direct listings) t=
here is no lockup agreement, because the whole point of the direct listing =
is just to make the stock freely tradeable. And so what happened in Slack i=
s that, on the first day, roughly 118 million shares were available for sal=
e under Slack=E2=80=99s registration statement, and roughly  165 million sh=
ares were available for sale=C2=A0without=C2=A0registration. And if you bou=
ght stock, there was no way to know which kind of stock you bought: You did=
n=E2=80=99t buy directly from the company in an IPO process; you just bough=
t on the stock exchange from an anonymous counterparty. If you bought =E2=
=80=9Cregistered shares,=E2=80=9D then technically you are allowed to sue S=
lack under section 11, just like in an IPO; if you bought =E2=80=9Cunregist=
ered shares,=E2=80=9D then you are not, just like in a mature public compan=
y. But there is no way of knowing which one you bought, so in practice you =
can=E2=80=99t sue under section 11.
Weird! One possible conclusion here is that, if you are a company consideri=
ng an IPO, a direct listing=C2=A0reduces your potential liability=C2=A0(and=
 that of your underwriters
  [2]
): If you do a direct listing, no one can sue you under section 11 for miss=
tatements in your prospectus; they have to meet the higher bar of proving f=
raud.
Another possible conclusion here is that, if you are a company considering =
an IPO, and you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want to do a direct listing, you ca=
n maybe get these benefits anyway? Just don=E2=80=99t sign a lockup! Let so=
me of your employees or other existing shareholders sell stock immediately,=
 as soon as the IPO prices. Then anyone who buys stock after=C2=A0the IPO c=
an=E2=80=99t prove that they bought stock=C2=A0from=C2=A0the IPO, instead o=
f from your employees.

