Schematically the way a special purpose acquisition company works is:
=09A sponsor raises, say, $200 million from retail investors and puts it in=
 a pot. This costs her perhaps=C2=A0a few million dollars in fees for lawye=
rs, bankers, accountants, etc.=09She looks for a private company to take pu=
blic.=09If she finds one, she negotiates a deal to take it public. After th=
ey sign a deal, they market it to the retail investors, who get to vote on =
whether to do the deal.
  [3]

=09If they vote no, or if she never finds a deal, then the retail investors=
 get their $200 million back and the sponsor gets nothing and loses her sta=
rtup costs.=09If they vote yes, then the target company goes public, it get=
s the $200 million, the retail shareholders get stock in the newly public t=
arget company, and the sponsor gets like $50 million of stock, for free,=C2=
=A0for her trouble.

Just from that schematic description you will notice that if a SPAC=C2=A0do=
es a deal, the sponsor makes $50 million, while if it doesn=E2=80=99t do a =
deal, the sponsor gets nothing and is out of pocket a few million dollars o=
f startup costs. A deal is good for the sponsor; no deal is bad for the spo=
nsor. Meanwhile the=C2=A0quality=C2=A0of the deal matters a lot to the reta=
il shareholders: If the deal is good, their stock goes up and is worth more=
 than the $200 million they paid for it; if it is bad, their stock goes dow=
n and is worth less. But it matters very, very little to the sponsor: If sh=
e gets $50 million worth of stock for free and the stock declines by 80%, s=
he still has $10 million worth of stock, which is way better than she=E2=80=
=99d do without the deal.
Therefore the sponsor=E2=80=99s incentives are:
=09Find the best deal she can get.=09But if the best deal she can get is ba=
d, do it anyway.=09
Market=C2=A0the deal aggressively: If the deal is bad, the shareholders wil=
l reject it, but if they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0know=C2=A0that it=E2=80=99s bad=
 they will accept it and the sponsor will get paid. Therefore it is in her =
interests to make them think that the deal is good, even if she knows it is=
n=E2=80=99t.

One thing that helped here is that, at the peak of the SPAC boom, there was=
 a  widespread and partially true belief that SPAC marketing could include =
financial projections, and that those projections could say whatever you wa=
nted. In a traditional initial public offering in the US, it is legally ris=
ky to give potential investors=C2=A0projections of future results, and so m=
ost companies don=E2=80=99t; in a SPAC, it was thought to be less risky to =
give projections, and so most companies did. These companies were often, li=
ke, flying-car companies with no operating history but grand plans, so the =
projections mattered a lot.
This is all rough and schematic but it also tells you everything you need t=
o know about SPACs. There were a lot of SPACs, especially in 2020 and 2021.=
 They did a lot of deals. The deals were, often, bad, especially as the SPA=
C boom went on: Sponsors had to find deals to get paid, target companies kn=
ew that, and they drove hard bargains. The deals were often bad, but their =
projections were often good. Then the stocks of a lot of the companies take=
n public by SPACs dropped, in part because the broad market dropped but als=
o in part because a lot of these deals were pretty bad.
And then the SPAC shareholders sued, saying, just, what I said above. You d=
on=E2=80=99t need to know much about the details of any particular SPAC to =
be like =E2=80=9Cah yes this is a gold mine for shareholder lawsuits.=E2=80=
=9D The standard mechanics of SPACs are all you need to know! Just write on=
e generic=C2=A0lawsuit and cut and paste the company names.=C2=A0
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Bailey Lipschultz reports:=C2=A0

The raucous boom in special-purpose acquisition companies =E2=80=94 which b=
ankrolled takeovers that resulted in back-door public offerings for busines=
ses seeking to sell everything from flying motorcycles to infrastructure in=
 space =E2=80=94 has spawned a wave of litigation, with dozens of cases fil=
ed by burned investors working their way through court.=C2=A0
In the last few months alone, they=E2=80=99ve taken aim at some of the most=
 well-known operators: Chamath Palihapitiya, the former Facebook executive =
who became the public face of the SPAC mania; billionaire Alec Gores; Bill =
Foley, owner of the NHL=E2=80=99s Las Vegas Golden Knights hockey team; and=
 British entrepreneur Richard Branson.
The lawsuits claim SPAC executives made millions by pushing through deals t=
hat allowed them to cash in their founder shares, the deeply discounted equ=
ity stakes that promised windfalls as long as they could find a company to =
buy. The arrangement provided a strong incentive to complete acquisitions e=
ven if lofty valuations and overly optimistic business plans posed long-ter=
m risks to other shareholders.
=E2=80=9CThe incentives were to close a deal, any deal,=E2=80=9D said Usha =
Rodrigues, a professor of corporate law at the University of Georgia School=
 of Law. =E2=80=9CThere were too many SPACs chasing too few targets and ine=
vitably companies went public that weren=E2=80=99t good candidates for the =
public market.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
More than 100 companies that merged with a SPAC, or about a quarter of thos=
e to complete deals since late 2018, have seen their shares tumble more tha=
n 90% since their debuts.=C2=A0

Yeah I mean stock went down, incentives were bad, that=E2=80=99s good enoug=
h for a lawsuit. You might not like it:
In a court filing, lawyers representing Foley, the hockey team owner who is=
 facing a lawsuit over his SPAC=E2=80=99s merger with the digital-payments =
platform Paysafe Ltd., denied any wrongdoing, saying the investor is follow=
ing a =E2=80=9Cone-size fits all=E2=80=9D approach echoing similar cases.=
=C2=A0
But one size really does fit all!=C2=A0

