One model of elite graduate business schools is that they are expensive two=
-year vacations for people who are already on a promising career track at b=
ig tech and finance companies. This is not necessarily the=C2=A0main=C2=A0m=
odel; probably you learn stuff. Still, here is Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Robb Man=
delbaum on the surprisingly weak job market for Harvard Business School stu=
dents this year:

In Cambridge, the first indications of trouble appeared last fall as the fu=
ll-time recruiting season got underway. Tech companies=E2=80=94in recent ye=
ars, among the top three destinations for HBS graduates=E2=80=94largely wit=
hdrew from recruiting. Varun Annadi, who=E2=80=99d come to Harvard from Goo=
gle, found to his surprise that he couldn=E2=80=99t even land an interview =
with his former employer. =E2=80=9CAnd I had internal referrals and an exce=
llent record of employment there,=E2=80=9D he says.
Things looked no better in the finance industry, also among the top three f=
ields sought out by HBS grads. Annadi points to a classmate who =E2=80=9Cwo=
rked in private equity before and has had, like, 20 interviews with various=
 PE shops=E2=80=94all of whom have said they=E2=80=99re extremely talented,=
 but they just aren=E2=80=99t hiring right now.=E2=80=9D

Would these people still have jobs at Google or in private equity if they h=
ad stayed at their jobs instead of leaving for Harvard? I don=E2=80=99t kno=
w; there have been a lot of=C2=A0layoffs, plus probably they learned someth=
ing at Harvard. But it might be=C2=A0harder for an employer to lay off a lo=
yal and productive employee than it is to just not hire a new MBA, and in a=
 tough economy, the people who took two years off to network in Cambridge m=
ight be less attractive than the people who didn=E2=80=99t.

