<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Slack</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a company does an initial public offering=
, it files a registration statement=C2=A0with the US Securities and Exchang=
e Commission=C2=A0with a prospectus containing=C2=A0financial statements an=
d a description of its business and other relevant details. If you buy stoc=
k in the IPO=C2=A0and=C2=A0the stock goes down, and if something in the pro=
spectus is misleading, you can sue the company, and the underwriters of the=
 IPO, for damages. You would sue under <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3=
VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc3aw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b4840e8" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">section=
 11</a> of the Securities Act of 1933, which lets you sue if the registrati=
on statement=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccontained an untrue statement of a material fact=
 or omitted to state a material fact required to be stated therein or neces=
sary to make the statements therein not misleading.=E2=80=9D In fact, if yo=
u=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>buy stock directly in the IPO, but buy i=
t in the open market the day or week or month after the IPO, you can also s=
ue under section 11: Your shares are =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=9D to the IPO=
, and you could have been misled by the company=E2=80=99s bad prospectus in=
to buying the stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, if you buy stock in a mature public compa=
ny years after its IPO, and the stock goes down, you can=C2=A0<em>also </em=
>sue the company. =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ=
2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MDEyM19NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDY=
wMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf8043b01" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">Everything is securities fraud</a>,=E2=80=9D I like to say. The company=
 puts out lots of public disclosures, and you can probably point to one of =
them and say "hey that was misleading, and when the truth came out my stock=
 went down.=E2=80=9D Technically here you would be suing under <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4ag/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7=
4cc0218" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> section 10</a> of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, wh=
ich makes it illegal for anyone to use =E2=80=9Cany manipulative or decepti=
ve device or contrivance=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cin connection with the purc=
hase or sale of any security.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, if you can, you would rather sue u=
nder section 11 of the =E2=80=9933 Act than section 10 of the =E2=80=9934 A=
ct. For one thing, it is easier to prove an =E2=80=9Cuntrue statement of ma=
terial fact=E2=80=9D than a =E2=80=9Cmanipulative or deceptive device or co=
ntrivance.=E2=80=9D (Lawyers say that section 10 requires =E2=80=9Cscienter=
=E2=80=9D: Roughly, you need to prove the company=C2=A0was lying, not just =
mistaken.) For another thing, section 11 lets you sue the underwriters =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the investment banks that led the IPO =E2=80=94=C2=A0while sect=
ion 10 doesn=E2=80=99t, because there are no underwriters, because there is=
 no offering.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so stock-drop lawsuits that stem from an I=
PO are more valuable than stock-drop lawsuits that don=E2=80=99t: If a comp=
any says something wrong in its IPO prospectus and the stock drops, its sha=
reholders have a good lawsuit; if a company says something wrong in its ann=
ual report years after its IPO and the stock drops, the shareholders have a=
 less good lawsuit. And this makes sense: The law is stricter on companies =
that are=C2=A0<em>going=C2=A0</em>public; it tries to make sure that compan=
ies introduce themselves to the public honestly and that their underwriters=
 are willing to vouch for them. Once a company has been public for a while,=
 there is a higher bar for complaining that its public filings are a trick.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few years ago there was a bit of a fad for <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMTEvZGlyZW=
N0LWxpc3RpbmdzLWFyZS1hLXRoaW5nLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1d=
G1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MDEmdXRt=
X2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0ce5f655" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  di=
rect listings</a>, in which companies went public without an IPO. Instead o=
f hiring an underwriter to sell a big block of stock at a fixed price, comp=
anies would just open for trading on the stock exchange one day, and start =
trading at whatever price the market settled on. When this started, it was =
a way to become a public company without selling stock: Existing shareholde=
rs (founders, employees, venture capitalists) were just allowed to sell sto=
ck one day, but the company itself did not raise money by selling stock. (S=
ince then, the stock exchanges have created rules to allow companies to <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTEtMjcvc29vbi1k=
aXJlY3QtbGlzdGluZ3Mtd2lsbC1yYWlzZS1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFV=
GRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MD=
EmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b0b992a" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  raise money using direct listings</a>.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One question is: If you buy stock in a direct =
listing, and the stock drops and you have complaints about the company=E2=
=80=99s disclosure, do you get to sue under section 11 (because it=E2=80=99=
s=C2=A0<em>basically=C2=A0</em>an IPO), or do you have to sue under section=
 10 (because it is=C2=A0<em>not actually=C2=A0</em>an IPO)?=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Slack Technologies Inc. went public through a =
direct listing in June 2019. It shot up to $38.62 on its first day of tradi=
ng, and then fell=C2=A0to as low as $20.13 by November. (It was acquired by=
 Salesforce Inc. for about $45 in cash and stock in July 2021.) People who =
bought early and saw the stock drop naturally sued, complaining that Slack=
=E2=80=99s disclosures were wrong. I don=E2=80=99t know what disclosures th=
ey had complaints about; that is rarely the point in these things. Instead,=
 the important question was whether they get to sue under section 11 or not=
. An appeals court ruled that they did, but Slack appealed to the US Suprem=
e Court, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31662=
572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vdXMtbGF3LXdlZWsvc3VwcmVt=
ZS1jb3VydC1jdXJicy1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci1zdWl0cy1pbi1wYXJ0aWFsLXNhbGVzZm9yY2Utd2l=
u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf46ee870" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  today Slack won</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US Supreme Court limited the ability of sh=
areholders to sue over misleading statements issued by companies when they =
go public through a direct listing, giving a partial victory to=C2=A0Salesf=
orce Inc.=E2=80=99s Slack unit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The justices on Thursday unanimously=C2=A0set =
aside=C2=A0a ruling that had let a shareholder suit go forward. Writing for=
 the court, Justice=C2=A0Neil Gorsuch=C2=A0said federal securities law auth=
orizes lawsuits over registration statements only by people who hold shares=
 issued under those documents. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The justices were considering a suit by Fiyyaz=
 Pirani, who alleges that Slack=E2=80=99s 2019 registration statement faile=
d to disclose the extent to which the company would have to provide credits=
 to customers over service disruptions. Salesforce acquired Slack in 2021.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Salesforce contends Pirani lacks legal standin=
g to sue under the 1933 Securities Act because he can=E2=80=99t prove he bo=
ught registered shares. The Supreme Court ruling leaves open the possibilit=
y that Pirani can show that at least some of the 250,000 shares he says he =
bought were registered.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmd=
vdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yMnBkZi8yMi0yMDBfMDk3Yy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBffe44=
9b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">the=C2=A0opinion</a>. The issue here is pretty strange. Basica=
lly the way it works is that, in an IPO, a company sells stock into the mar=
ket, and anyone who buys stock that day, or the next day, or the next week,=
 necessarily buys shares that were registered and sold in the IPO. In a typ=
ical IPO, the company=C2=A0(and some of its private shareholders: founders,=
 venture capitalists, etc.) will register with the SEC and sell a big block=
 of stock,=C2=A0perhaps 20% of the outstanding shares, and these are the sh=
ares that are available for public trading that day and the next day and th=
e next week. The=C2=A0<em>rest=C2=A0</em>of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0the 80=
% still owned by founders, employees, venture or private-equity backers, et=
c. =E2=80=94=C2=A0will not be available for trading for a while, mostly bec=
ause of lockup agreements preventing insiders from selling it.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Gorsuch:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To prevent the stock price from fa=
lling once public trading begins, underwriters may require insiders to cons=
ent to a =E2=80=9Clockup agreement=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a commitment to hold th=
eir unregistered shares for a period of time before selling them on the new=
 public market.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This means that every share that changes hands=
 is =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=9D to the IPO: 100% of the publicly traded sha=
res were sold in the IPO, so if you buy stock that week you definitely boug=
ht IPO shares issued by the company under a registration statement. And the=
 way the law works is that, if you buy shares =E2=80=9Ctraceable=E2=80=9D t=
o the IPO and the IPO prospectus, you can sue under section 11 for misstate=
ments in the prospectus.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a direct listing, similarly, some of the bi=
gger shareholders have to register their share sales, and so there will be =
a registration statement and prospectus. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZl=
cy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3NjQ5MjUvMDAwMTYyODI4MDE5MDA4MTI1L3NsYWNrNDI0Lmh0bQ/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6164a7b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Here is Slack=E2=80=99s</a>. But ot=
her shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0small employee shareholders, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0can sell their stock immediately without registration, and (as is oft=
en true of direct listings) there is no lockup agreement, because the whole=
 point of the direct listing is just to make the stock freely tradeable. An=
d so what happened in Slack is that, on the first day, roughly 118 million =
shares were available for sale under Slack=E2=80=99s registration statement=
, and roughly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3166=
2572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3NjQ5MjU=
vMDAwMTYyODI4MDE5MDA4MTI1L3NsYWNrNDI0Lmh0bSNzMDE3RkRCMDVBRENBNDdBODg0REY1Nj=
dEOEYzODBCMjc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53414cac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 165 million share=
s</a> were available for sale=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>registration. And =
if you bought stock, there was no way to know which kind of stock you bough=
t: You didn=E2=80=99t buy directly from the company in an IPO process; you =
just bought on the stock exchange from an anonymous counterparty. If you bo=
ught =E2=80=9Cregistered shares,=E2=80=9D then technically you are allowed =
to sue Slack under section 11, just like in an IPO; if you bought =E2=80=9C=
unregistered shares,=E2=80=9D then you are not, just like in a mature publi=
c company. But there is no way of knowing which one you bought, so in pract=
ice you can=E2=80=99t sue under section 11.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weird! One possible conclusion here is that, i=
f you are a company considering an IPO, a direct listing=C2=A0<em>reduces y=
our potential liability=C2=A0</em>(and that of your underwriters<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>): If you do a direct listing, no one can sue you under section 11 for =
misstatements in your prospectus; they have to meet the higher bar of provi=
ng fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another possible conclusion here is that, if y=
ou are a company considering an IPO, and you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</=
em>want to do a direct listing, you can maybe get these benefits anyway? Ju=
st don=E2=80=99t sign a lockup! Let some of your employees or other existin=
g shareholders sell stock immediately, as soon as the IPO prices. Then anyo=
ne who buys stock <em>after=C2=A0</em>the IPO can=E2=80=99t prove that they=
 bought stock=C2=A0<em>from=C2=A0</em>the IPO, instead of from your employe=
es.</p>
