<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schematically the way a special purpose acquis=
ition company works is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A sponsor raises, say, $200 million f=
rom retail investors and puts it in a pot. This costs her perhaps=C2=A0a fe=
w million dollars in fees for lawyers, bankers, accountants, etc.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">She looks for a private company to take pub=
lic.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If she finds one, she negotia=
tes a deal to take it public. After they sign a deal, they market it to the=
 retail investors, who get to vote on whether to do the deal.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they vote no, or if she never =
finds a deal, then the retail investors get their $200 million back and the=
 sponsor gets nothing and loses her startup costs.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">If they vote yes, then the target company goes public, it =
gets the $200 million, the retail shareholders get stock in the newly publi=
c target company, and the sponsor gets like $50 million of stock, for free,=
=C2=A0for her trouble.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just from that schematic description you will =
notice that if a SPAC=C2=A0does a deal, the sponsor makes $50 million, whil=
e if it doesn=E2=80=99t do a deal, the sponsor gets nothing and is out of p=
ocket a few million dollars of startup costs. A deal is good for the sponso=
r; no deal is bad for the sponsor. Meanwhile the=C2=A0<em>quality=C2=A0</em=
>of the deal matters a lot to the retail shareholders: If the deal is good,=
 their stock goes up and is worth more than the $200 million they paid for =
it; if it is bad, their stock goes down and is worth less. But it matters v=
ery, very little to the sponsor: If she gets $50 million worth of stock for=
 free and the stock declines by 80%, she still has $10 million worth of sto=
ck, which is way better than she=E2=80=99d do without the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Therefore the sponsor=E2=80=99s incentives are=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Find the best deal she can get.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But if the best deal she can get is ba=
d, do it anyway.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Market=C2=A0</em>the deal aggressively: If the deal is bad, the shareho=
lders will reject it, but if they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>know=C2=A0</em>tha=
t it=E2=80=99s bad they will accept it and the sponsor will get paid. There=
fore it is in her interests to make them think that the deal is good, even =
if she knows it isn=E2=80=99t.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that helped here is that, at the pea=
k of the SPAC boom, there was a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1pcG9zP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA2MDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBca42d077" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> widespread and partially true belief</a> that SPAC=
 marketing could include financial projections, and that those projections =
could say whatever you wanted. In a traditional initial public offering in =
the US, it is legally risky to give potential investors=C2=A0projections of=
 future results, and so most companies don=E2=80=99t; in a SPAC, it was tho=
ught to be less risky to give projections, and so most companies did. These=
 companies were often, like, flying-car companies with no operating history=
 but grand plans, so the projections mattered a lot.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all rough and schematic but it also te=
lls you everything you need to know about SPACs. There were a lot of SPACs,=
 especially in 2020 and 2021. They did a lot of deals. The deals were, ofte=
n, bad, especially as the SPAC boom went on: Sponsors had to find deals to =
get paid, target companies knew that, and they drove hard bargains. The dea=
ls were often bad, but their projections were often good. Then the stocks o=
f a lot of the companies taken public by SPACs dropped, in part because the=
 broad market dropped but also in part because a lot of these deals were pr=
etty bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the SPAC shareholders sued, saying, j=
ust, what I said above. You don=E2=80=99t need to know much about the detai=
ls of any particular SPAC to be like =E2=80=9Cah yes this is a gold mine fo=
r shareholder lawsuits.=E2=80=9D The standard mechanics of SPACs are all yo=
u need to know! Just write one generic=C2=A0lawsuit and cut and paste the c=
ompany names.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31662572.286417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDEvc3BhY3MtZnVlbC1uZXctYm9vbS1sYXdzdWl=
0cy1hcmUtcGlsaW5nLXVwLWluLWNvdXJ0cy1hY3Jvc3MtdXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYwMTIzX01PTk=
