jMwNjAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB59a08635" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Bailey Lipschultz reports</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The raucous boom in special-purpose acquisitio=
n companies =E2=80=94 which bankrolled takeovers that resulted in back-door=
 public offerings for businesses seeking to sell everything from flying mot=
orcycles to infrastructure in space =E2=80=94 has spawned a wave of litigat=
ion, with dozens of cases filed by burned investors working their way throu=
gh court.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the last few months alone, they=E2=80=99ve =
taken aim at some of the most well-known operators: Chamath Palihapitiya, t=
he former Facebook executive who became the public face of the SPAC mania; =
billionaire Alec Gores; Bill Foley, owner of the NHL=E2=80=99s Las Vegas Go=
lden Knights hockey team; and British entrepreneur Richard Branson.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsuits claim SPAC executives made millio=
ns by pushing through deals that allowed them to cash in their founder shar=
es, the deeply discounted equity stakes that promised windfalls as long as =
they could find a company to buy. The arrangement provided a strong incenti=
ve to complete acquisitions even if lofty valuations and overly optimistic =
business plans posed long-term risks to other shareholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe incentives were to close a deal, =
any deal,=E2=80=9D said Usha Rodrigues, a professor of corporate law at the=
 University of Georgia School of Law. =E2=80=9CThere were too many SPACs ch=
asing too few targets and inevitably companies went public that weren=E2=80=
=99t good candidates for the public market.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than 100 companies that merged with a SPA=
C, or about a quarter of those to complete deals since late 2018, have seen=
 their shares tumble more than 90% since their debuts.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah I mean stock went down, incentives were b=
ad, that=E2=80=99s good enough for a lawsuit. You might not like it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a court filing, lawyers represe=
nting Foley, the hockey team owner who is facing a lawsuit over his SPAC=E2=
=80=99s merger with the digital-payments platform Paysafe Ltd., denied any =
wrongdoing, saying the investor is following a =E2=80=9Cone-size fits all=
=E2=80=9D approach echoing similar cases.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But one size really does fit all!=C2=A0</p>
