<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Cambridge, the first indications of trouble=
 appeared last fall as the full-time recruiting season got underway. Tech c=
ompanies=E2=80=94in recent years, among the top three destinations for HBS =
graduates=E2=80=94largely withdrew from recruiting. Varun Annadi, who=E2=80=
=99d come to Harvard from Google, found to his surprise that he couldn=E2=
=80=99t even land an interview with his former employer. =E2=80=9CAnd I had=
 internal referrals and an excellent record of employment there,=E2=80=9D h=
e says.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Things looked no better in the finance industr=
y, also among the top three fields sought out by HBS grads. Annadi points t=
o a classmate who =E2=80=9Cworked in private equity before and has had, lik=
e, 20 interviews with various PE shops=E2=80=94all of whom have said they=
=E2=80=99re extremely talented, but they just aren=E2=80=99t hiring right n=
ow.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Would these people still have jobs at Google o=
r in private equity if they had stayed at their jobs instead of leaving for=
 Harvard? I don=E2=80=99t know; there have been a lot of=C2=A0layoffs, plus=
 probably they learned something at Harvard. But it might be=C2=A0harder fo=
r an employer to lay off a loyal and productive employee than it is to just=
 not hire a new MBA, and in a tough economy, the people who took two years =
off to network in Cambridge might be less attractive than the people who di=
dn=E2=80=99t.</p>
